Up 2-0 in a 7-game series across NBA/NHL/MLB the historical result is about 80% leader wins the series, but is substantially lower for World Series for which it is only ~68%. Interestingly, these odds change very little if the trailer wins game three (2-1), and if the teams then split the next two games (3-2). If the leader goes up 3-0 or 3-1, however, the odds get very small for the trailer. So... I'm going to predict that KC wins. I don't see much reason to change that unless the Mets can tie the series at 2-2 at which point I'll have to re-evaluate. http://www.whowins.com/tables/up20.html

Blue Jays had a 57% winning percentage and Mets had a 56% winning percentage, we can say they are close to evenly matched on a statistical basis, so we assume that each game is a 50/50 guess. Jays have won 2 games already, so we have 5 games left. We need the Jays to win 2 more times. Since the odds are the same as a coin flip, we ask how many combinations can we flip heads twice flipping 5 times, then we divide that number by the total possible coin flip combinations. The answer to the number of combinations is 2^5=32 total combinations and number of ways to flip at least two heads is 26 b/c math. So 26/32 is 81%. However, I add bias above this favoring Jays on momentum.

In the American League the Jays and Yankees are both the expected contenders with win %s of .572 and .553 respectively. In central it is the Royals with .586, the potential Twins at .513 and in the west it is Texas with .546 and Houston as a potential wildcard with .523. The Angels are still possible with .513 as well. For making the world series, the AL favorites are Blue Jays and Royals, followed by Rangers, Yankees, and Astros. Texas will likely play the Jays, with Jays a heavy favorite. Astros and Yankees will pace off in the wildcard with New York the favorite and that winner will play the Royals. The eventual teams in the world series will most likely be the Jays, Royals, or Rangers in order.
